'''Takayanagi Chōshizuka Kofun''' (高柳銚子塚古墳) is a {{ill|Keyhole-shaped kofun|ja|前方後円墳}} located in {{ill|Kisarazu, Chiba|ja|木更津市}}, Chiba Prefecture.

== Overview ==

The kofun is located on a sand dune 1.8 kilometers north of the {{ill|Gion-Nagasuka Kofun Cluster|ja|祇園・長須賀古墳群}}, which includes late-period chief kofun such as {{ill|Kane no Suzu Kofun|ja|金鈴塚古墳}}. Its main axis aligns northeast-southwest, and it was originally over 110 meters long, making it the third-largest kofun in Chiba Prefecture.<ref name=Chiba/> 

However, during the late Meiji period, railway construction destroyed the front section. Additionally, the rear section was heavily damaged during World War II due to the establishment of an army anti-aircraft gun command post. Cylindrical {{ill|haniwa|ja|埴輪}} fragments recovered from the tumulus suggest its construction dates back to the mid-{{ill|5th century|ja|5世紀}}.

