'''Takayanagi Chōshizuka Kofun''' (高柳銚子塚古墳) is a {{ill|Keyhole-shaped kofun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Kisarazu, Chiba|ja|木更津市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Chiba Prefecture.

== Overview ==

The kofun is located on a sand dune 1.8 kilometers north of the {{ill|Gion-Nagasuka Kofun Cluster|ja|祇園・長須賀古墳群|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which includes late-period chief kofun such as {{ill|Kane no Suzu Kofun|ja|金鈴塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Its main axis aligns northeast-southwest, and it was originally over 110 meters long, making it the third-largest kofun in Chiba Prefecture.<ref name=Chiba/> 

However, during the late Meiji period, railway construction destroyed the front section. Additionally, the rear section was heavily damaged during World War II due to the establishment of an army anti-aircraft gun command post. Cylindrical {{ill|haniwa|ja|埴輪|qq=draft|qq=draft}} fragments recovered from the tumulus suggest its construction dates back to the mid-{{ill|5th century|ja|5世紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

<gallery>
File:高柳銚子塚古墳出土 埴輪.JPG|Haniwa<br/>{{small|Exhibited at the {{ill|Kisarazu Local History Museum Kane no Suzu|ja|木更津市郷土博物館金のすず|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.}}
</gallery>

